# chameleon profile auto-merge
#
# Copy this file to your repo as `.gitattributes` (or merge into existing one)
# to enable automatic profile merge resolution via chameleon-mcp.
#
# This prevents painful JSON merge conflicts when two developers run
# /chameleon-refresh on parallel branches.

.chameleon/profile.json     merge=chameleon
.chameleon/archetypes.json  merge=chameleon
.chameleon/rules.json       merge=chameleon
.chameleon/canonicals.json  merge=chameleon
.chameleon/conventions.json merge=chameleon

# idioms.md is hand-curated, append-only, and preserved across refresh, so two
# branches that each ran /chameleon-auto-idiom or /chameleon-teach must keep
# BOTH sets of idioms on merge. The chameleon driver detects markdown idioms
# and unions them by slug (git's built-in `merge=union` is NOT used: it
# line-unions the fenced code blocks and unbalances the ``` fences, corrupting
# the file). With the driver registered (see below) the merge is clean; without
# registration git falls back to visible conflict markers you resolve by hand —
# never silent corruption.
.chameleon/idioms.md        merge=chameleon

# The transaction sentinel and the regenerated markdown companions have no
# structural merge, but they MUST still route to the driver: without it a
# conflicting merge writes raw conflict markers INTO these files, and a
# marker-laden COMMITTED or principles.md is live profile state the runtime
# then reads. The driver declines to merge them, which leaves your side's
# content whole and the file flagged conflicted — resolve by accepting either
# side and running /chameleon-refresh, which regenerates the content.
.chameleon/COMMITTED          merge=chameleon
.chameleon/principles.md      merge=chameleon
.chameleon/profile.summary.md merge=chameleon

# Generated index artifacts (exports_index.json, reverse_index.json,
# function_catalog.json) are intentionally NOT routed to the merge driver:
# they have no structural merge, and the correct resolution for a conflict
# on them is to accept either side and run /chameleon-refresh, which
# regenerates all three from the merged repo state. A conflict on them is
# harmless to the runtime: markers break the JSON parse and every loader
# fails open.

# To register the merge driver, run once in your repo (or globally with --global):
#
#   git config merge.chameleon.name "chameleon profile merge"
#   git config merge.chameleon.driver "/path/to/chameleon/scripts/chameleon-merge-driver.sh %O %A %B %P"
#
# Replace /path/to/chameleon with your installed plugin dir, e.g.
#   ~/.claude/plugins/cache/chameleon/chameleon/<version>
# (The old `chameleon-mcp merge_profiles ...` form does not work — that console
#  script only launches the stdio MCP server; the shell driver above is the real
#  merge driver.)
#
# Without registration, git falls back to its default conflict-marker behavior.
